16
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Maybe you could tell folks a little bit about that because I'm going to assume not everybody is familiar with your story.

17
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:31,000
So I grew up in Belgium. I was born in Leuven, which is one of the oldest university towns in Europe.

18
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:43,000
And then I grew up in Antwerp, two Polish parents who were both the sole survivors of their entire family of the Nazi concentration camps.

19
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:47,000
And they by fluke arrived to Belgium.

20
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:52,000
There was no they had a permit there for about three months and then they decided to stay.

21
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:57,000
And so they ended up being another five years illegal refugees in Belgium.

22
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:04,000
And I was educated in Antwerp, which was a Flemish city.

23
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:13,000
So I did 12 years of schooling in Flemish, but we spoke also French and Yiddish and German and Polish in the house.

24
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:23,000
And that just was the way it was. It's the air that you breathe. Nobody made a big deal out of speaking all these languages and learning them.

25
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,000
So that's the basics.

26
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:33,000
When you finished your education, your high school education, what was the next step for you?

27
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Where did you go after that?

28
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:43,000
The first thing I did after I finished high school was come to the United States to travel for almost two months.

29
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:50,000
And I ended up hitchhiking across the US and seeing the country in a way that I probably will never see it again.

30
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:55,000
And then I went to study in Jerusalem. So I went to the Hebrew University.

31
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:01,000
That's where I did my undergraduate. And then I started my graduate school there.

32
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:18,000
And I came to Boston to Leslie College to finish the second year of my master's program and to start my training in family therapy at the Cambridge Family Institute and to work at Mass Mental Health, which was one of the Harvard Medical School hospitals.

33
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:23,000
And then basically I never used my return ticket.

34
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:24,000
And here I am.

35
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:28,000
Let's go back to the hitchhiking trip.

36
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:33,000
What made you decide to venture from Europe to the United States in the first place?

37
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:39,000
