39
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:53,000
Since I was traveling at age 14, a major way that you traveled when you were curious and broke was to hitchhike.

40
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,000
So it was perfectly in fashion at that time to do so.

41
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:07,000
And why the United States? Because it was the bicentennial and there were cheap cargo flights that took you from Belgium to the U.S.

42
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:16,000
Capitol Airlines was like this first invention of old planes refurbished for people who didn't need much comfort.

43
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:22,000
And no, I had a Greyhound pass. We, I was with my boyfriend, we had a Greyhound pass and we thought we would be traveling to the U.S.

44
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:23,000
Capitol.

45
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:26,000
And I thought we would be traveling with Greyhound.

46
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
But every time my finger went up, it went so well.

47
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And I got invited into the homes of every kind of person that lives in this country and the kindness of strangers, really, like in ways that I probably would never have access to today.

48
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,000
So it was the whole West Coast.

49
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:48,000
It was Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama and then the Northeast.

50
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:54,000
That's that it turned out this way because of a whole adventure.

51
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Basically, I had lost my we lost our wallet and our travel checks, if you remember that concept and and everything.

52
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
And we didn't have phones at the time, of course.

53
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:11,000
So somebody found it and this man came to pick us up and at a downtown station in L.A.

54
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,000
And he invited us to his house.

55
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:19,000
And from that moment on, this trip took on a whole different personality for us.

56
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
And that was that.

57
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:37,000
Seven weeks later, I had just, you know, really had an insider's look that that innocence and curiosity allowed me to and a good sense of street smartness, which you need when you hitchhike, of course.

58
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Did that in part sort of give you a little bit of an affection for American culture?

59
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:52,000
And is that maybe part of the reason why you ultimately ended up setting up roots here?

60
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:55,000
Actually, no.

61
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
I was fascinated.

62
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:03,000
You know, I came before I came to study in Boston.

63
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:04,000
I came for another trip.

64
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:07,000
I did another hitchhiking trip in Mexico for quite a few weeks.

65
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:12,000
And then I went all the way from Merida to Miami to Quebec.

66
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:18,000
So and then I did a third trip where I spent the entire summer in New York City in the late 70s.

67
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,000
So you can imagine it was a different city.

68
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:22,000
No, I liked it.

69
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:29,000
I was very curious, but I had no intention ever of coming to live in what we call at a time in America.

70
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:38,000
I came to study because I had the opportunity to come to Cambridge and nobody in my family had gone to university like this.

71
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:45,000
And I was the first and, you know, I had read Borges and I thought Cambridge was a fascinating place to come and study.

72
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
And I should take this opportunity.

73
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And I had no idea that I would stay.

74
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
So I stayed in Cambridge for a couple of years.

75
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
And then I came to New York thinking I have a place to live.

76
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:57,000
A couple of years.

77
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:01,000
And then I came to New York thinking I have to do the New York adventure for one year.

78
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:06,000
And I came with my husband now, who was boyfriend then.

79
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
And I really didn't think I would stay.

80
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:12,000
But I fell in love with New York.

81
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
That I knew.

82
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:21,000
And it's always been very clear to me that it would be Manhattan or abroad, that my real affection was for New York City.

83
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:27,000
You could be anything and every part of you in one place.

84
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:31,000
And I had always looked for a place to integrate the multiple parts of me.

85
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:34,000
And this seemed to be the place where I could do so.

86
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:48,000
Now, I want to kind of go back to something you said at the outset, which is both your mother and your father were the sole survivors from their families, meaning their parents, their siblings, their aunts, uncles, everybody perished.

87
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,000
Is that that I understand that correctly?

88
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:51,000
Yes.

89
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:57,000
My father came from a family of nine and he was the youngest.

90
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:00,000
My mother came from a family of seven.

91
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:04,000
Every single one of their siblings were married with seven to ten children.

92
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:09,000
And so each of them lost two hundred people about.

93
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:19,000
And they basically met on the day of liberation on the roads where people were looking for other people from the same area that could tell their children.

94
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:23,000
If anybody else had survived, you know, it was.

95
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,000
And that's kind of how they met up.

96
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:30,000
And yeah, that was it.

97
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
They were the only ones.

98
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:37,000
Do you have a sense of what permitted them to be the survivors?

99
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:49,000
Do you attribute it to sheer luck or I mean, the odds seem almost unimaginable given the circumstances of their periphery.

100
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:54,000
So the war for them starts in thirty nine because they live on the German side of Poland.

101
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:57,000
So this is a very long war, six years about.

102
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:00,000
My mother spent the first year in the woods.

103
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
She's eighteen.

104
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:07,000
She hides in the woods, which is really where she suffered the most.

105
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:18,000
And she actually went by herself to a labor camp, a men's labor camp, because she had in her mind that if she can work in the kitchen or laundry,

106
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:23,000
that somehow at least she will wake up every morning in the same place.

107
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:29,000
Whereas in the woods, she had no idea and she she couldn't take the dread anymore.

108
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,000
She proceeds to go to nine different camps over the five years.

109
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:39,000
And my father went to fourteen of them, including a stint in in Siberia.

110
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,000
When I would ask them.

111
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:46,000
There were generally a series of three points.

112
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:49,000
The first one was luck, simply sheer luck.

113
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:53,000
I wasn't selected every morning when they chose a thousand people.

114
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
Somehow it didn't pick me.

115
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:59,000
The second one was we wanted to live.

116
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:05,000
We wanted to live without maybe somebody is waiting for us somewhere and we were going to live with dignity.

117
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:11,000
So my mother describes mending her socks, folding her clothes,

118
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:16,000
doing basic things that kind of maintain their sense of humanity.

119
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:28,000
And for my father, my father basically in the last year and a half created a kind of a black market in the kitchen where he had more access to potatoes.

120
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:31,000
It wasn't potatoes and potato peels.

121
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:38,000
And he managed to feed about 60 young people that all survived thanks to that, because it meant that they could go work.

122
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:42,000
And as long as you could work, you had a chance of at least surviving, including him.

123
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:46,000
He fed the Germans, the Nazis, the SS guards.

124
00:10:46,000 --> 00:11:00,000
And and I think feeling that he could help others gave him a sense that of of of agency, of mastery, of purpose of I can do something here.

125
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,000
So luck was a piece of it.

126
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:07,000
It wasn't the only thing, but it always was mentioned.

127
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:24,000
So when you were growing up, I assume that you had friends who were not from that background and therefore they would have, quote unquote, normal things like grandparents and cousins and aunts and uncles, things that you did not have.

128
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:28,000
Was that contrast stark for you as a young child?

129
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:33,000
So I grew up in a kind of a dual situation.

130
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:38,000
I grew up, we had a clothing store in a working class neighborhood.

131
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:40,000
I lived above the store.

132
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:42,000
I worked in this store.

133
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:45,000
We were like the immigrant family on the block.

134
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:47,000
My parents had accents.

135
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,000
They didn't speak very well.

136
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:54,000
It's like in any neighborhood where you have that that store that is owned.

137
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
But instead of a food store, it was a clothing store.

138
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,000
You know, that's when I am born.

139
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:01,000
But I come 12 years after my brother.

140
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:05,000
So this is by then there is a store that then didn't start like this.

141
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Right.

142
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:18,000
And my father on occasion would kind of say, you know, he would put their hand on the shoulder of a client, of a customer and just say, we went through some very bad things during the war.

143
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:23,000
Like and I would think, like, how would they relate to any of this?

144
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Then there was the Jewish community that we were a part of where most of the people had numbers on their arms.

145
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:37,000
So the first question you ask at three years old is, why don't I have a grandma or a grandpa?

146
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:39,000
And then the second time is, what is this number?

147
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:42,000
And the third time is why don't I have uncles and aunts?

148
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:45,000
And so you ask these very and you don't.

149
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:47,000
It's not just because you see other children.

150
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:50,000
It's because you read children's books.

151
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:53,000
And in the children book is a story of a family.

152
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:55,000
And it has a few generations.

153
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,000
And we had none of that.

154
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:03,000
And we had about five pictures that show that they, you know, they had managed to save a few pictures.

155
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:07,000
So that said, there were these other people.

156
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:12,000
And so the Jewish community that I grew up in was all Holocaust survivors.

157
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:14,000
That's this was normative for me.

158
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:20,000
This was a very normal, you know, it's a refugee community that you only know refugees.

159
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:23,000
But then in the store where these other people.

160
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:40,000
You've spoken a little bit about it, but I find it to be kind of amazing how your parents survival changed their outlook on life and how that impacted your outlook on life.

161
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,000
Say a little bit about that.

162
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:47,000
There's sort of there's zest for life, if you will.

163
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:53,000
You know, one of the things my dad always used to say is we came from harsh circumstances.

164
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:55,000
We were used to the bitter cold.

165
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:59,000
I used to carry bags of cement on my back.

166
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:08,000
I was we were much better prepared than those who came from Greece or the Mediterranean or, you know, urban environments.

167
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:15,000
There was something about being from kind of peasant stock, basically, that prepared them for hardship.

168
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:23,000
And I don't know, you know, the interesting thing is why does this story stay with me out of a thousand others that he has told me?

169
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:42,000
They talked a lot. So it's like what what, you know, today, this is not really what you ask, but it's often, you know, when I get asked a question like this and I start to answer it, I realize a thousand questions that I didn't get to ask.

170
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:51,000
That I just took the story as it was told, like a Swiss cheese with all the holes in it and never kind of said, but how did you go from here to there?

171
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:56,000
It's just like we went and, you know, like she mended her socks.

172
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:59,000
How did you do that? Where did you find the needle?

173
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:06,000
Where did you find, you know, all these very granular details that I have no real answer to.

174
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:14,000
But I think what I got was a few different things.

175
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:25,000
The first thing I got, which actually really came back very strongly during the pandemic this year, you know, was the notion that everything can disappear in a split second.

176
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:30,000
Don't ever think that what you have is there to stay and is yours.

177
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:37,000
And on the one hand, it prepares you for catastrophes, for disasters, for change.

178
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:51,000
And on the other hand, you can never fully, fully settle and you never, you never fully calm because you don't know that the ground you sit on could not at any moment, you know, open up.

179
00:15:51,000 --> 00:16:09,000
That's, I think, probably the most important thing is that sense of impermanence, the sense of loss, the mass of loss, the collective loss of not just people, but life, community, legacies, generations of stuff.

180
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:20,000
That's another thing. I think I have a real sense of what that is, you know, and when I, I plumb into mine when I need to realize that.

181
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:28,000
I have a real sense of mind when I need to reach in other people's experience of loss like that.

182
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:36,000
But also, and dread, I mean, that goes with that. And then on the other side, yes, this enormous zest for life.

183
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:41,000
I mean, they were not just there to work and rebuild. My parents were real bon vivant.

184
00:16:41,000 --> 00:17:01,000
They really enjoyed to party, to sing, to dance, to, and that in my work and in my personal life, but in my work when I around trauma and around pain and suffering, I, you know, I have a reference for how one comes back from there.

185
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:12,000
How one loves again, celebrates again, parties again, in a way that is not just them, but they happen to be the ones that I knew the best.

186
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:22,000
And these things have very much influenced me in my thinking and in my outlook on the world. I mean, yeah, there's lots of other things.

187
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:36,000
So if on the one hand, it's entirely remarkable that your parents survive the ordeal that they were placed in, it seems equally remarkable that they weren't permanently scarred by it.

188
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:58,000
And if we've talked about some of the factors that may have contributed to their ability to survive what they did for six years, what do you contribute to their ability to come out the backside and experience everything you just said, which is because I have to imagine that there are many people who survived concentration camps, but they were never the same again.

189
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:15,000
They were never able to form meaningful relationships. The PTSD of the experience effectively left them dead, even though they were still breathing. So why, I mean, I'm guessing your parents didn't have access to MDMA assisted psychotherapy for PTSD and world class psychotherapists.

190
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,000
I'm guessing they did this somehow on their own.

191
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:32,000
No, but they had access to something else. See, my mother in the 50s went to the big professor at the university in Leuven. And basically, he kind of said to her, what you experienced, what can't just come back from.

192
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:44,000
And there is nothing, there is no medication or treatment for this kind of stuff. And she had nightmares, and she had massive eruptions sometimes.

193
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:57,000
And she, you know, she'd go and check the door a few times in the night at that time and stuff. So we didn't call it PTSD, we just call it survivor syndrome, actually was the name at the time.

194
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:25,000
But she had access to what today are called a spa. My mother did talaso therapy, mud therapy, walking on wet grass, all the things that today are part of the wellness treatments that are all traditional things that were done in the Bath of Eastern Europe, in Czechoslovakia, in Hungary, in Poland.

195
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:44,000
And she went every year for a month to the spa, where she was doing bath and water and mud and big jets of frozen water, the stuff that you do when you go from hot to cold. This was like traditional medicine.

196
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:54,000
So that's the stuff she did, to calm her nerves, which was called at the time calling you, you know, you had nerve issues, nervousness.

197
00:19:54,000 --> 00:20:08,000
The other thing, because I have said, I mean, it is a thing I wrote in Mating in Captivity that kind of followed me around afterwards, where I said that I was interested in that very question.

198
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:23,000
What made some people want to live? What feeds the liveness? What is this antidote to death or deadness? And I remember describing my observation between those who did not die and those who came back to life, you know, those who could never trust,

199
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:34,000
and those who reconnected again, etc. But I think what really, and this is very relevant for today, what my parents had was a strong sense of community.

200
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:52,000
So, you know, all these people come out of the camps and first they go to DP camps, to temporary camps. And the amount of babies that were conceived there, because all these people wanted to have children to know as a way of proving that they are alive, that they are human.

201
00:20:52,000 --> 00:21:05,000
That they can still procreate. And that in itself is such an act of healing. You know, you rebuild, you didn't destroy it all, you didn't sever all connection.

202
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:16,000
You know, there will be a future, there will be more of us. That's the first thing. Then this community comes together and they have gatherings for the survivors of town, such and such.

203
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:27,000
For the survivors of camps, such and such. They plant trees, they celebrate, they tell stories, they fundamentally understood something that today we're trying to bring in.

204
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:38,000
That is that such a, what is called today collective trauma, that was called psychosocial trauma, demands collective resilience. They didn't try to do anything on their own.

205
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:50,000
You know, now the first years, they don't talk much. They arrive to these foreign countries and most of the time people don't really want to hear much of what they've gone through. You know, it's like, you tell two sentences and people can't hear anymore.

206
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:52,000
Meaning even amongst each other, not?

207
00:21:52,000 --> 00:22:07,000
No, no, no. With each other they tell, but they don't always have to tell. You see, it could be this kind of short, you know, that camp was a bad camp. That SS God, you did not want to be under him.

208
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:22,000
You know, I managed in that winter. They had all these sentences like that, that just shorthand and everybody knew what was the reference. Everybody knew what it came back to. So to each other they talked a lot.

209
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:35,000
And you know, I've always had this image that I was told because it's such a powerful thing. Every Sunday my parents played cards. Friends came over and they played cards. So they're playing gin, rami and stuff.

210
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:45,000
And as they were playing with these cards, somebody would just suddenly say, whatever happened to John, you know, Morris, John Mitchell, John, whatever.

211
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:58,000
Oh, this one was gassed. This one was murdered. It didn't make it. He went to Australia and I couldn't believe what I was hearing. It was like there was no child development approach in my house.

212
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:20,000
You know, nobody looked as if there's a child there to hear all of this. It was done in this affectless way. It was no affect. Horrors were told in that this what today we would call dissociation, but for the purpose of survival and regeneration.

213
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:48,000
It was a very good natural defense. And I think that what is interesting about that group, which is really the first time that people understood the concept of adult trauma, because until then it was all about first five years of your life, is that they came up with some of the most adaptive, resilient ways of going about things without ever seeing a shrink.

214
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:59,000
Without any access to mental health, just something inside their own tradition that they had, you know, that history. This was not the first time Jews were having a rough time in history, right?

215
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:13,000
They did these resources really were gleaned from a culture that is collective in nature and it's not the only one for sure. So that's, I think, really what helped them more than anything else.

216
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:29,000
Walks in the woods was a ritual. You needed to go into nature. This is like, you know, everybody's writing about that this pandemic here. Something that about them knew that being in the forest is healing.

217
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:45,000
No, recently you wrote something on Mother's Day, actually, about your relationship with your mother and you wrote about all the positive things and many of the positive things that your mother did for you.

218
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:57,000
But at the same time, there were things she didn't do for you. And it's left you with a feeling of ambivalence, at least with respect to some of the mother-daughter things that maybe weren't there.

219
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:13,000
How did that unfold for you as you went from being a child to an adolescent? And I assume at the time you didn't think this was abnormal because you had nothing to compare it to. I assume this was a retrospective reflection.

220
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:33,000
I would say from the time I was an adolescent to the time I was an adult is really more the sequence, you know. So it's very interesting. I have not talked often about this, but I just was tired of hearing about Mother's Day and Hallmark Heart Mother's Day.

221
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:51,000
And I thought there's so many people who have complicated relationships with their mother. Maybe we should put that on the table for a change. So I whip this thing out on Sunday because it's very easy for me with a good dose of humor to describe my mother.

222
00:25:51,000 --> 00:26:04,000
And what's phenomenal is thousands of people that are writing to me basically say, this is my mother. This is my mother. So I know she's not unique, you know. And she comes in every culture and she comes in every color.

223
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:24,000
But basically she had this thing with the evil eye, right? She was a very superstitious woman. So this whole idea that you shouldn't say good things to your kid because it will blow their head. She took that to the very concrete level, you know.

224
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:39,000
And so, you know, she had this notion that she's there to tell you what other people will not tell you. And that's usually not the good stuff. And so she was true to herself till the end. She didn't say one good word to me ever.

225
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:41,000
How old were you when she died?

226
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:47,000
I was, she was 80 and I was 42.

227
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:52,000
So by the time she died, you had already achieved a lot of professional success.

228
00:26:52,000 --> 00:27:11,000
I was, no, not completely. Yes, in my field, but I hadn't written mating in captivity. I actually started to write mating after she passed away. And I remember saying, this is the first time I'm actually doing something that I'm not sure I can do.

229
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:15,000
And I don't think I could ever have done this when she was alive.

230
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:23,000
For fear that she would be critical of you saying, why are you doing this? You don't have the, you don't have the experience to do this or something like that?

231
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Yeah, I mean, because every time I made a decision, I had to have confidence one time for me and one time for her anxiety.

232
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:39,000
I had to prove to her whatever it was, this was true for the hitchhiking trip to this was true for going to study in Jerusalem. This was true for coming to live in New York.

233
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:52,000
Everything, everything I decided, you know, she would challenge me, challenge me, challenge me. And so I had to, I had to have inside of me a sense that I knew that I can do it.

234
00:27:52,000 --> 00:28:08,000
I have to succeed at this, you know, not to prove her wrong, but just to be able to do what I want. I wasn't, you know, it wasn't to defy her. But this time I began to write and I thought to myself, I have no idea.

235
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:18,000
I had, I remember saying, I've always done things that somewhere inside of me, I think I'm capable of doing.

236
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:26,000
You know, these are sentences that I remember saying back then, and this is the first time that I'm taking something out. I have no idea.

237
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:47,000
But her voice isn't there to make me feel like I have to be sure I'm allowed to do something without knowing. And I'll do the best I can and I'll pour my soul into this. But that's all I have rather than I know I can, which was the stance I had to have before then.

238
00:28:47,000 --> 00:29:01,000
So I think the ambivalence that you're asking about is really, you know, it's not uncommon that you have a family and the mom becomes the strict one. She's the stern one. She's the more critical one. And my dad is sugar candy.

239
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:20,000
He's the sweetest, you know, the sweetest, kindest, loving, adoring dad. And what you begin to understand once you start to study family therapy is that, of course, he's always kind and loving and adoring because he leaves some of the dirty job to her.

240
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:42,000
She has to put the limits. She has to, you know, basically put the limits, do the discipline, do all the stuff that he doesn't like to do. And I began to understand that the good parent and the bad parent or the soft parent and the harder parent, that's a construct that is not just a matter of personality.

241
00:29:42,000 --> 00:30:00,000
Because my mother has also very, she had tremendous charisma and she was funny and brilliant and all of that too. That in fact, it's because of how he acts that that puts her in this role. And this role then is already the quota is filled so he doesn't really have to do it.

242
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:16,000
And once I saw that, I began to see my dad is not the all good, that he actually leaves her alone, comes home three hours later, doesn't call to tell her, leaves her standing with all the cooked food in the kitchen.

243
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:29,000
And of course, when he comes home, she's all pissed and yelling that he doesn't respect her or that she's there, you know, standing there like an idiot in her, you know, and me, instead of thinking, stop screaming.

244
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:32,000
I began to say, why did you just do this to her?

245
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:53,000
You know, in your beautiful loving way, but you just stood her up. And once you begin to reorganize the movie and the interpretation of the movie, then you suddenly realize she's actually not only the negative, you know, my anger goes to her and my love goes to him kind of thing.

246
00:30:54,000 --> 00:31:06,000
And that's when you begin to experience the ability to hold contradictory emotions at the same time. And that's ambivalence. Ambivalence is the ability to hold both ends.

247
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:18,000
I love you. And I also have a lot of anger toward you. And those two are coexisting inside of me, rather than I split off one part and then I attribute it somewhere else.

248
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:36,000
And once I began to do that, then I was able to diffuse her things, you know, if she was critical or something, you know, I had a way of joking with her that basically didn't allow her to enter under my skin.

249
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:54,000
And I just could really say, you know, all kinds of diffusing tricks that I had learned, basically my favorite one, which because I've used it with so many people in my own therapy work afterwards was to just give her a kiss on the cheek and just say, I so appreciate how you're trying to make me a better person.

250
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:08,000
But I want you to know, I think you've done a good job. I think I've got I'm where you I'm where you I think you would want me to be. So if you want, you can go try to improve others.

251
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:17,000
It worked very well for me. I would laugh as I said it, instead of feeling the wrath mounting inside of me.

252
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:23,000
So what drew you to therapy as a career?

253
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:46,000
I would ask myself what drew me to psychology first. So I am a teenager. I am a teenager at that time. I have a very contentious relationship with my mom. We do a lot of good screaming on occasion. I am in a school system that is extremely traditional.

254
00:32:47,000 --> 00:32:53,000
The student doesn't matter. Only the content matters. The material matters, you know.

255
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:11,000
And I'm thinking, you know, I start to read these alternative education books and I start to read Victor Frankl and I start to read Bruno Betelheim and I start to read Three Children of Summerhill and R.D. Lang and anti psychiatry.

256
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:29,000
And I just I become very, very interested in why do we feel what we feel? How come I'm having dreams about Hitler and Nazis and you know, it's not my life. I didn't go through that. Why do I have those dreams? What does that do to me?

257
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:44,000
And how do people get along better with their parents? You know, at that time, sometimes, you know, when things were really, really tough with her, I had this idea that if I could disappear, then I would see if she ever misses me.

258
00:33:45,000 --> 00:34:00,000
You know, and if she then but I had this fantasies of how can I disappear for a while and put the fear in her that she may have lost me and then see if she actually cares about me. And then I thought, where does that come from? Why would I want to do such a thing?

259
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:18,000
And this is the beginning of my interest in psychology and in you and in reading about human relationships, which I then did profusely. And and then I also realized I actually am quite good at this. People come to confide in me all the time. All my friends.

260
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:36,000
I see this. I see I see what's not visible in relationships. And, you know, everybody thought because of my languages that I should be an interpreter or maybe a journalist or a lawyer because I could argue my case, a litigator.

261
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:44,000
And I decided I think psychotherapy could be a very interesting profession or a spy, by the way, you'd be you would have been a great spy.

262
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:47,000
That's right. I never thought of that one.

263
00:34:48,000 --> 00:35:01,000
So when you found yourself in Boston, you're you're now going through your graduate program. What is your first job career? You know, your first your first step into your professional career. Is it family therapy?

264
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:11,000
No, my first, first job was at the hospital as an expressive art therapist working on the psychiatric unit.

265
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:28,000
And because I had also had the whole adolescence and young adulthood in the theater and I had done a lot of puppetry and I thought to study expressive art therapies would be a very interesting way of bringing together the arts as a modality, as a psychotherapeutic modality.

266
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:41,000
And I just worked two years first in the hospital as an expressive art therapist, primarily with groups, actually, sometimes with families, but mostly with groups.

267
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:53,000
And there was something missing. I felt like there must be more plus it. You're at the bottom of the totem pole when you're an expressive arts therapist. It's like you're the recreation therapist.

268
00:35:53,000 --> 00:36:07,000
After the doctors have gone by the therapist, the psychologist, then, you know, keep them busy. And I just thought that that isn't going to go very well for me, you know, to be in a profession that is not valued when I think it is so incredible.

269
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:22,000
Something is off. So I was with Jack, I was talking to Jack at the time and who was just a colleague at that moment. And my kind of mentoring me slightly through my thesis.

270
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:38,000
And he said, I think you would be interested in family therapy. It's more contextual. It's more anthropological. It's more intercultural. It takes all the other pieces into account the way that you have done.

271
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:49,000
I was writing about cultural, religious and racial identity. This was too small for me. I needed a field that I could, you know, that was more expansive.

272
00:36:49,000 --> 00:37:08,000
And the revolution was to begin to think in systemic terms away from the individual intra psychic model into the interpersonal and societal or contextual model. That just opened up a gate for me. And then I went to work at MassMental.

273
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:15,000
And slowly I thought, I'm not sure that the hospital setting is the best setting for me.

274
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:21,000
How does that family therapy work in a hospital setting? When you say hospital setting, do you mean inpatient setting?

275
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:24,000
Yes, yes, inpatient.

276
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:34,000
So does that mean that you're taking care of psychiatric inpatients as individuals or you're helping families of inpatients?

277
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:45,000
Yes, with the identified patients. So I did it both inpatient and outpatient. And basically, yes, you do sessions with the whole family.

278
00:37:46,000 --> 00:38:01,000
But it's not just who is in the room. It's how you think about what is a patient in family therapy language. The patient is not just a patient because they feel certain things or they are struggling with things inside of them.

279
00:38:01,000 --> 00:38:21,000
The patient has a function in the family, is often assigned by the family. That is the person who's allowed to struggle and suffer out loud amongst a group of ascetic people who are just like holding it all in. That's just one tiny example.

280
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:39,000
So you work with the system and you try to understand what led this person to want to commit suicide, what led this person to not eat, what led this person to destroy themselves or whatever the issues are.

281
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:54,000
And that notion that things are interconnected was also what I had experienced. I knew that some of the things I was feeling wasn't just because I was born this way. It was in my dynamic with my parents, with my mother in particular.

282
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:16,000
And when you study family therapy, you do genograms, you look at intergenerational transmission. And so you constantly are studying yourself as you are learning the paradigm. And at no time did I think, oh, this just applies to me. This is a fascinating other way to look at things.

283
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:23,000
Now, when you studied, when you did your master's, it was focused on family therapy?

284
00:39:24,000 --> 00:39:26,000
My master's is an expressive arts therapy.

285
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:42,000
Okay. So that's what took you to your first role. So one thing that is interesting to me about psychology versus medicine. In medicine, your postgraduate training, your residency really prepares you for what you're going to do in your career.

286
00:39:42,000 --> 00:40:06,000
And frankly, many people don't do much training beyond that, even though obviously one should. But it seems that in psychology, you have to reinvent yourself. I mean, if you want to make the leap from expressive arts therapy to family therapy, you're not going to go back and do another master's degree or do another clinical internship or something like that.

287
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:16,000
So how beyond your own experience, how are you finding mentors and or sharpening the tool of your trade?

288
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:34,000
You can be a practicing clinician who every few years decides to learn one more modality, one more theoretical paradigm. It's endless. It's absolutely endless.

289
00:40:35,000 --> 00:40:44,000
You can have an interest in a topic. I'm interested in the area of trauma. I'm interested in eating disorders. I'm interested in anxiety disorder. This is one way to organize your interest.

290
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:59,000
But you can also say, I'm interested in working with families. And at that time, this was the head is a family therapy. There were five schools of family therapy, structural family therapy, strategic family therapy, feminist family therapy, intergenerational.

291
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:28,000
You know, these were you had a good 10 years of learning just between those five. Right. You can say, I want to learn, you know, now there is the neuroscience. The neuroscience have come in and they have so many interesting new things to say about how people regulate and co-regulate each other in relationships. I need to know that because I want to be able to use that in my work. So my frame remains the same. I am a couple of therapists, a family therapist, do individual work as well.

292
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:55,000
But I need to understand the new things that we know about the brain. Then there is a place everybody's talking mindfulness. I need to know everything that mindfulness can tell me about working in relationships. Then, you know, it's that way that you basically if you are a curious person in mental health and in psychotherapy per se, which is one practice of mental health, it is an endless, endless school.

293
00:41:56,000 --> 00:42:20,000
And I have, you know, there I am admired those who sometimes continue. They're like, I have colleagues who just like throw themselves into a new approach and spent 500 hours, you know, honing that skill. And then, you know, you have CEUs as well, Peter. There is an incentive that makes you continue to go and learn.

294
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:37,000
But I think the knowledge of human beings, which I think is not different in medicine in that sense, is endless. And there is a new way of thinking. And then there becomes a dominant way of thinking. And then for 10 years, everybody thinks like that.

295
00:42:38,000 --> 00:42:52,000
And then, you know, the truth of today becomes the joke of tomorrow. And then we move on to a new paradigm. And it's amazing how you're just, you know, depending on when you enter the field, you basically rode the wave of the moment.

296
00:42:53,000 --> 00:43:07,000
If I was in the 19th, late 19th century, I would have been a psychoanalyst. And you would have thought of medicine very differently than you do today. In a way, it shows you the social construct of those fields.

297
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:17,000
They are sciences and they are humanities, but they are also completely immersed in the time that they are, you know, in the context of the moment.

298
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:34,000
And if your CEUs are as valuable as our CEUs, they don't offer too much. Our CEUs are, they're something that we do simply to maintain our licensure. But I'm still looking for CEUs that teach much valuable content.

299
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:56,000
In fact, the ones, at least for me, that I find most valuable are the ones that are so far outside of my area of expertise that I can actually learn something. But, you know, the ones that are generally close to what I do are not that helpful, which of course then makes me question how helpful the ones are that are so outside of my area, because they may be equally far from what's likely reality.

300
00:43:56,000 --> 00:44:09,000
But so you're going along, you're doing family therapy, you're now transitioning obviously from inpatient to outpatient. I assume you're, is this when you moved from Boston back to New York?

301
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:11,000
Yep. Yep.

302
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:16,000
And everything's going well. And then how did Bill Clinton change your life?

303
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:17,000
So there's a little bit of a road to Bill Clinton. But you asked me because I think this training thing, CEU, is a really important thing. So I, and I'm going to trace this back to my mother. I think that because of how critical she could be, I did often seek a role in the role of the

304
00:44:46,000 --> 00:45:02,000
mentors. I was very drawn to people who saw something good in me. I was drawn to people who believed in me. I was drawn to people who thought I can do certain things. It just, I would melt when somebody would do that.

305
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:15,000
And then I began to actually really seek these mentors, not just stumbled upon them as a counselor in a summer camp or things like that. And this is kind of how I learned. I asked people who I wanted to be,

306
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:31,000
who I wanted to learn from, if I could be their shadow. And I just was like a disciple that, you know, an apprentice that watches the craft being done and learns from incredible clinicians.

307
00:45:31,000 --> 00:45:49,000
I mean, then I come to New York and that's when I meet one of my next mentors, Salvador Minuchin, who I have spoken about because my two main mentors have actually passed away in the last two years. One by old age and one by suicide.

308
00:45:50,000 --> 00:46:12,000
So I've been thinking a lot about these things. And I basically started to work at the 92nd Street Y and then started to work privately because that's what, you know, it had to do with papers and immigration and license and green cards and all of that stuff.

309
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:37,000
And I basically did it the way that I knew my immigrant parents did. You hustle, you find a way, you enter in, you know, that kind of a thing. And I had, by the time this Clinton affair arrives and by the time I start to write meeting, yes, I had a very nice psychotherapy practice.

310
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:54,000
I would teach, I was at NYU in the medical school as a clinical instructor. I was lecturing and I had developed a real specialty in the area of working with mixed couples and families, intercultural, interracial, interreligious couples and families.

311
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:08,000
Why? Because the way I could build a private practice in New York City is because I knew languages. I didn't know much about therapy yet, but I knew languages and these people wanted to speak their language with me. And that's how this began.

312
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:23,000
And I had three supervisors who checked on everything I did. And that's how I began. And by the time the Clinton scandal arrives, I just didn't want to write a book about mixed couples.

313
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:39,000
That was the main thing. I began to feel like I'm ready for a new subject, but I need a portal topic and I like topics that open up to me, that connect to theology, anthropology, sociology, psychology, you know, big, like you.

314
00:47:39,000 --> 00:48:07,000
The CEUs take place in a different field. You know, I like that too. And I don't know, I just got inspired by the story because it kind of really was this, what is this American attitude to sexuality and to sexuality as a matter of national political agenda for that matter and to, you know, how do I make sense of this whole thing?

315
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:17,000
And then I wrote this article in 2003 in an obscure magazine that was known only in our field. And that changed everything around.

316
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:35,000
And now I've read this obscure article in this obscure magazine and you comment on being at a conference and noting the fundamental difference that all the people at the conference who were American had versus all of the non-Americans.

317
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:42,000
Say a bit more about that.

318
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:58,000
I think that one way to say it is on a cultural level, there's been a real push to see sex as a risk factor in America. Sex itself is the risk factor.

319
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:13,000
Whereas I think the European notion and the public health notions in Europe is that sex is a natural part of human development. Being irresponsible is a risk factor. That changes everything.

320
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:28,000
And so I don't think that clinicians in the field of psychotherapy is free from that. I studied couples therapy and family therapy without one hour about the subject of sexuality.

321
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:34,000
How can that be in a culture where sexuality is so central?

322
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:50,000
And in a love culture, I'm not talking about just the modern ideology of love puts that dimension front and center. How can we do couples therapy and not ever talk about it? Years. Something is missing.

323
00:49:50,000 --> 00:50:08,000
And the field had organized itself in a very interesting way to never have to talk about it because it said if there are sexual problems, it's the consequence of relationship problems. Therefore, focus on the relationship, fix the relationship and the sex will follow.

